\begin_layout Section
Advanced installation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A lot of work has been put into fine-tuning gvSIG's default behaviour, but
 in some situations (such as complex multi-user environments and automated
 roll-outs), different tweaks may be necessary for an optimal installation.
 The following provides some hints for these cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
User-defined SRS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the past, gvSIG used to manage user-defined spatial reference systems
 inside its application directory, which could lead to numerous problems
 in multi-user environments (change conflicts, missing write-permissions,
 etc.).
 This has now been changed so that gvSIG will by default manage custom SRS
 definitions inside the user's settings folder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it will only do so if the files 
\emph on
usr.script
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
usr.properties
\emph default
 are present in the user settings folder.
 Otherwise, it will revert to the old behavior, which is to read those two
 files from 
\emph on
gvSIG/extensiones/org.gvsig.crs
\emph default
 inside the gvSIG application folder.
 The startup script for gvSIG OADE will automatically copy some default
 SRS definitions to the user settings folder if they are not already present.
 This means that by default all users will have their own SRS definitions
 available in their personal settings folder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Shadowbox
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If you already have some customized SRS, then make sure to copy them out
 of 
\emph on
gvSIG/extensiones/org.gvsig.crs 
\emph default
folder and into your user settings folder so you can continue using them.
 You should always do this before you deinstall a version of gvSIG or reinstall
 into the same directory.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you do not like any of this, then you can also explicitly set a folder
 to be used for this purpose, via the new environment variable 
\emph on
GVSIG_CONF_DIR
\emph default
, as explained below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Startup scripts
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Startup-scripts"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On all platforms, the actual gvSIG application is only launched after a
 startup script has been run that carries out a number of tasks, such as
 ensuring that sensible default application settings, style files and templates
 are always present in the user settings folder.
 It also makes sure that the Java environment is properly set up.
 On Linux and Windows, the startup scripts are contained in the 
\emph on
bin
\emph default
 subfolder of the gvSIG application folder.
 On Mac OS X, the location is the folder 
\emph on
Contents/MacOS
\emph default
 inside the application package.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The name of the script is 
\emph on
gvSIG.sh
\emph default
 on Linux, 
\emph on
gvSIG.bat
\emph default
 on Windows and 
\emph on
preJava
\emph default
 on Mac OS X.
 The Linux and Mac OS X scripts configure the entire Java environment.
 On Windows, 
\emph on
gvSIG.ini
\emph default
 contains most of the settings for Java.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
