\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environment variables
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Environment-variables"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There a few environment variables that you can set to control the way the
 gvSIG OADE startup scripts handle user settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
GVSIG_CONF_DIR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, gvSIG will manage all user preferences, style files, and several
 other data files in a folder called 
\emph on
gvSIG
\emph default
 inside the user's home directory.
 If you wish to change this (which can be useful to e.g.
 separate the preferences of different gvSIG versions), then set 
\emph on
GVSIG_CONF_DIR
\emph default
 to the name of a different folder.
 If that folder does not exist, it will be created the next time gvSIG is
 started and filled with default settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
GVSIG_CRS_DIR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This variable, if set, will tell gvSIG where to manage user-defined spatial
 reference system definitions.
 It has to be set to the name of a folder that already exists on your system
 and has the appropriate access permissions.
 The custom SRS definitions database, consisting of the two files 
\emph on
usr.script
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
usr.properties,
\emph default
 has to be present in that folder and be readable.
 If this variable is set to a wrong value, then gvSIG will fail to start!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Java properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you do not want to use the gvSIG OADE startup scripts and wish to control
 the behaviour described above directly, then you can use the Java properties
 equivalents of the environment variables and pass them directly to the
 Java VM.
 The general syntax is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
java -D<property>=<value>
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
E.g., to set the user preferences folder and SRS storage, the Linux startup
 script does this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Verse
java -DgvSIG.confDir="$MY_CONF_DIR" -DgvSIG.crsDir="$GVSIG_CRS_DIR" [..]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
gvSIG.confDir
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the equivalent of 
\emph on
GVSIG_CONF_DIR
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
gvSIG.crsDir
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the equivalent of 
\emph on
GVSIG_CRS_DIR
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Customizing the Java VM (32/64 bit)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Java-customization-(32/64"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This software contains 32 bit JNI (Java Native Interface) bindings for raster
 data and projection support.
 It cannot be run from a 64 bit JVM.
 If you do not wish to or cannot use the bundled 32 bit JRE that comes with
 gvSIG OADE and instead use a 64 bit JRE/JVM installed on your system, then
 you must force that JVM into 32 bit mode via the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

-d32
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Shadowbox
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If you attempt to run gvSIG OADE on a 64 bit JVM and use any raster data
 or projection functionality, then you will get an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

UnsatisfiedLinkError
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 and the data will fail to load into the project View.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On Mac OS X and Linux you will find the variable definitions that set the
 Java interpreter to use (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "sub:Mac-OS-X"

\end_inset

 for an example) and the memory settings at the top of the startup script.
 E.g., on Linux you will see something like this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
# Path to an alternative Java executable used to run gvSIG.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
# Uncomment the line below to use your system's default Java.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
#JAVA=java
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
# Java tuning settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
INI_HEAP=1024M
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
MAX_HEAP=1024M
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variable 
\emph on
INI_HEAP
\emph default
 (equals Java setting 
\emph on
-Xms
\emph default
) is the initial size of the Java memory heap, 
\emph on
MAX_HEAP
\emph default
 (same as Java setting 
\emph on
-Xmx
\emph default
) is its maximum size.
 You can set both variables to the same value to tell gvSIG the maximum
 size of a single memory chunk it can claim at a time (not the total memory
 it can use while it runs!).
 On systems with plenty of RAM, it can make sense to increase the Java heapspace
 to be able and work with very large data sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, on 32 bit systems there are strict limits to how high you can go
 with the memory settings.
 On Linux and Mac OS X, people have reported settings of up to about 2000M
 to be working, on Windows the limit is significantly lower at about 1500M.
 It is safe to experiment with this; if the settings are too high than gvSIG
 will simply crash on startup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On Windows, the memory settings are in 
\emph on
gvSIG.ini.
 
\emph default
Look for the line that starts with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

command = 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, it has the Java memory settings, which you can change as needed:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
command = #JAVA# [..] -Xms512M -Xmx512M [..]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you whish to change the Java Virtual Machine to use on Windows, then
 look for the variable 
\emph on
JAVA_HOME, 
\emph default
also in 
\emph on
gvSIG.ini
\emph default
.
 However, please note that the JRE bundled with the Windows version of gvSIG
 OADE includes a number of additional DLL files in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 directory.
 If you wish to run gvSIG OADE using a different JRE, then you need to also
 copy all of these into your new JRE's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 directory!
\end_layout

